tence of segregation by race and class. This book shows how innovations that increase the flexibility of property law can address critical issues of neighborhood control and community composition that have been simmering unresolved for decades -- and how homeownership itself can be reinvented to better deliver on its promises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommons. 0aHomexPhilosophy. 0aHomeowners' associationsxLaw and legislation. 0aLand usexLaw and legislation. 0aRight of property. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh0 cprintz978030012244240uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015502040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300155020423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300155020/original  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles